Major League Baseball executives may be rejoicing over this year=E2=80=99s =
World Series matchup between the league=E2=80=99s wealthiest clubs and bigg=
est markets, the Dodgers and the Yankees, a far cry from last year=E2=80=99=
s underwhelming Texas-Arizona sitch. But the reality is that this auspiciou=
s outcome overlays some thorny and nuanced and enduring economic challenges=
=2E

MLB, after all, is the most federalized of the Big Four sports leagues. Sur=
e, it has packages with ESPN, Amazon, Roku, and Apple. But local fandoms, p=
rolific schedules, and the longtime reliable revenue from local cable have =
made it harder for the league to collectively exploit the media value of it=
s product, as has become the modus operandi in the NBA, with its $77 billio=
n media rights package, and the operating procedure de rigueur in the NFL, =
with its current (and
somehow seemingly underpriced) $110 billion decade-plus deal. And now this =
financial reality has come into stark relief as the regional sports network=
 business continues to implode via small-scale extinction events like Diamo=
nd=E2=80=99s long-gestating bankruptcy and Comcast=E2=80=99s grinfucking. O=
ver the past two seasons, MLB has taken back the rights to six of its teams=
: the Padres, Diamondbacks, Rockies, Guardians, Twins, and Brewers.

Last week, I chatted with MLB commissioner Rob Manfred, who recently signed=
 a five-year extension, about his strategy to lead the league through the p=
latform transformation. Manfred predicted =E2=80=9Ca significant accelerati=
on in the number of teams that give their rights to MLB Media,=E2=80=9D but=
 acknowledged that this process will take considerable time. MLB can=E2=80=
=99t put together this sort of package until it amasses more of its teams=
=E2=80=99 local rights, which expire along various timelines. The Dodgers, =
for example, are contentedly locked into
their lucrative, $334 million deal=E2=80=94almost the precise value of thei=
r payroll=E2=80=94until 2038. And the Yankees, with their own R.S.N. and O.=
T.T. option, may have other theories of the case.

So far, the teams that have turned over their rights are cognizant that the=
y will bring in less local revenue, at least initially. But Manfred predict=
s teams will wind up making more in the long run with a hybrid local media =
strategy, one that combines cable carriage with local broadcast deals and p=
ooled direct-to-consumer offerings that might entice the trillion-dollar ma=
rket cap streaming players, like Amazon, Apple, and Google. =E2=80=9CThe in=
herent value of our content is going to bring us back to and beyond where w=
e were,=E2=80=9D Manfred said. =E2=80=9CI would predict today that that tro=
ugh will be shorter. I certainly am sensing in my private conversations=E2=
=80=94and we=E2=80=99ve seen it publicly=E2=80=94that new media companies a=
re becoming aggressive sooner than some people expect.=E2=80=9D

