John Ourand: MLB made headlines this month when it took back the rights to =
the Guardians, Twins, and Brewers=E2=80=94in addition to the Padres, Diamon=
dbacks, and Rockies=E2=80=94whose rights were held by Diamond Sports. From =
a 50,000-foot view, what is your plan with these local rights?

Rob Manfred: I think it=E2=80=99s important to remember that we didn=E2=80=
=99t begin with a grand plan about local rights or being in the business of=
 doing games locally. In a lot of ways, we stepped into a situation where w=
e didn=E2=80=99t have a great alternative. The R.S.N. was going bankrupt, a=
nd we needed to make sure that we got our games out locally. As we started =
to think about the landscape more generally, we came to realize that our br=
oadcast product needed to be more national. The difficulties with the R.S.N=
=2Es presented an opportunity for us to get
into a more centralized media strategy and get closer to the model that Com=
missioner Adam Silver used in his recent round of NBA negotiations. The R.S=
=2EN.s were really good for us from a f=
inancial perspective, but they did not=
 give us a full opportunity [to optimize our] reach.

What I=E2=80=99d like to see happen over time is, we redo our national deal=
s and convert some of that local inventory into national inventory, which i=
n turn increases our reach. We own the outer market rights already; if we c=
ontrol local rights as well, we can sell anything, anywhere, and you don=E2=
=80=99t just have to sell in your market. I=E2=80=99d like to get into a mo=
de where if it=E2=80=99s not in a national package, the consumer has the ab=
ility to go in and buy whatever he wants to watch, no matter where it is. A=
nd we get rid of that questionable business concept of the blackout.

Are you confident that you=E2=80=99re going to be able to bring big-market =
teams=E2=80=94the Dodgers, the Yankees, the Cubs,
for example=E2=80=94into that sort of system, which is going to ask them to=
 share more than they=E2=80=99re used to?

=E2=80=9CConfident=E2=80=9D is a funny word. I think there is a path forwar=
d that involves media and other really significant industry issues that cou=
ld put all the clubs in a position to come together. And the point I=E2=80=
=99d make about that is, the trends that are affecting the R.S.N.s right no=
w, we=E2=80=99re seeing them first in our smaller markets. And that=E2=80=
=99s not surprising, right? But those trends are so fundamental, sooner or =
later, they=E2=80=99re gonna affect everyone. And I do think there=E2=80=99=
s an opportunity in that problem.

I=E2=80=99ve always viewed the MLB=E2=80=99s untraditional streaming deals =
with Roku and Apple as some sort of test. What have you learned from them?

I think Apple, in particular, has been really creative on the production en=
d. And there are learnings there that have been useful to us; some things w=
orked, some things didn=E2=80=99t. Our traditional
broadcasts are kind of the same as they=E2=80=99ve been for a long time. Ev=
erything from graphics to announcers, Apple experimented with, and we=E2=80=
=99ve learned from that.

On the business side, I think maybe the biggest issue to talk about is the =
difference between having a paywall and not. We=E2=80=99ve had Apple in fro=
nt of a paywall, we=E2=80=99ve had it behind a paywall; we=E2=80=99ve had R=
oku in front of a paywall. I think the discussion and the differences betwe=
en the distribution mechanisms that Apple and Roku use, respectively, get t=
o the underappreciated business issue in broadcast for us, and that=E2=80=
=99s reach.

For years, we focused on dollars, understandably. But I think when you have=
 a live business that=E2=80=99s as robust as ours=E2=80=94where 72 million =
people a year go through the gates=E2=80=94reaching the fans with your broa=
dcast is really important in terms of driving them to the ballpark, which i=
s another really important part of our business.

The biggest
complaint about baseball for decades has been how old the fan base is. That=
=E2=80=99s starting to turn around. Why is that?

I think there are several reasons. I do think the changes we=E2=80=99ve mad=
e to the way the game is played on the field are a big part of it. We did r=
eally fundamental research about what fans wanted to see. And I think we=E2=
=80=99re putting out there a more action-packed, tighter, quicker game that=
=E2=80=99s appealing to young people. Secondly, I think that we have been b=
lessed with an infusion of young and extraordinary talent, combined with a =
different attitude about interacting with fans, being accessible to fans, p=
articularly being accessible on social media platforms where young people l=
ive. Then the third thing=E2=80=94and this one gets overlooked=E2=80=94I th=
ink the clubs have done a phenomenal job with what I refer to as the progra=
m in the stadium. Now we see so many alternatives=E2=80=94more flexible sea=
ting and ticketing arrangements that are designed to meet the
desires of younger fans.

From the Cheap Seats

On ABC simulcasting more =E2=80=98MNF=E2=80=99 games: =E2=80=9CThis hurts u=
s. I just don=E2=80=99t understand how ESPN can defend their highest-in-the=
-industry affiliate fees to MVPDs like Comcast when they decide to share th=
eir most valuable programming with a =E2=80=98free=E2=80=99 broadcast on AB=
C.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94A local-ad-sales executive

On what to call MLB=E2=80=99s automated strike zone: =E2=80=9CI understand =
that Rob Manfred doesn=E2=80=99t like the term =E2=80=98robot ump=E2=80=99 =
and would rather use =E2=80=98automated strike zone=E2=80=99=E2=80=94which =
I assume will be shortened to ASZ and pronounced =E2=80=98ASS.=E2=80=99 Is =
that better?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94A D.C. lawyer

One of a dozen emails I received about Jon Kelly=E2=80=99s The Backstory th=
is weekend: =E2=80=9CKelly is so much fun to read. His description of peopl=
e reading your newsletter is just so fun.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94A sports media =
executive

See you Thursday,
John

