lleges are increasingly focused on managing N.I.L. monetization rather than=
 financing infrastructure upgrades. Alas, college sports are changing at wa=
rp speed, as Virginia=E2=80=99s outgoing coach <b>Tony Bennett </b>reminded=
 us last week. And these shrines are memorials to the velocity of change.<b=
r/><br/></li><li><i>A World Series lead-in</i>: On
Friday, Fox will lead out of Game 1 of the Yankees-Dodgers World Series int=
o a Rutgers-USC college football game across town. The World Series is sche=
duled to start at 8 p.m. ET from Dodger Stadium, and Rutgers-USC is schedul=
ed to kick off at 11 p.m. ET at the L.A. Coliseum. (Ironically, both games =
involve teams from New York and Los Angeles.) If the World Series goes into=
 extra innings and runs past 11 p.m., Fox will carry the football game on F=
S1.<br/><br/>Over the years, broadcast TV networks have had a tough time co=
nvincing leagues to use the most popular programming from <i>other</i> spor=
ts as a lead-in=E2=80=94partly, of course, because none of them wants to he=
lp their competitors draft off their audiences. (It was <i>highly</i> unusu=
al when NBC used the Rams-Bengals Super Bowl to tee up the 2022 Winter Olym=
pics=E2=80=94the first time that a network had used a sporting event as the=
 lead-out from a Super Bowl since the =E2=80=9970s.) But Fox, as usual, has=
 been the most aggressive
employer of this tactic. Last year, the network scheduled a Michigan State-=
Arizona college basketball game immediately after the Packers-Lions Thanksg=
iving game. Not surprisingly, it still stands as the most watched college b=
asketball game Fox has ever carried.</li><br/><li><i>Congrats, I guess=E2=
=80=A6</i>: Congratulations to WNBA commissioner <b>Cathy Engelbert</b>, wh=
