x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Major League Baseba=
ll executives may be rejoicing over this year=E2=80=99s World Series matchu=
p between the league=E2=80=99s wealthiest clubs and biggest markets, the Do=
dgers and the Yankees, a far cry from last year=E2=80=99s underwhelming Tex=
as-Arizona sitch. But the reality is that this auspicious outcome overlays =
some thorny and nuanced and <i>enduring </i>economic challenges.<br/><br/>M=
LB, after all, is the most federalized of the Big Four sports leagues. Sure=
, it has packages with ESPN, Amazon, Roku, and Apple. But local fandoms, pr=
olific schedules, and the longtime reliable revenue from local cable have m=
ade it harder for the league to collectively exploit the media value of its=
 product, as has become the <i>modus operandi </i>in the NBA, with its $77 =
billion media rights package, and the operating procedure <i>de rigueur </i=
>in the NFL, with its current (and
somehow seemingly underpriced) $110 billion decade-plus deal. And now this =
financial reality has come into stark relief as the regional sports network=
 business continues to implode via small-scale extinction events like Diamo=
nd=E2=80=99s long-gestating bankruptcy and Comcast=E2=80=99s grinfucking. O=
ver the past two seasons, MLB has taken back the rights to six of its teams=
: the Padres, Diamondbacks, Rockies, Guardians, Twins, and Brewers.<br/><br=
/>Last week, I chatted with MLB commissioner <b>Rob Manfred</b>, who recent=
ly signed a five-year extension, about his strategy to lead the league thro=
ugh the platform transformation. Manfred predicted =E2=80=9Ca significant a=
cceleration in the number of teams that give their rights to MLB Media,=E2=
=80=9D but acknowledged that this process will take considerable time. MLB =
can=E2=80=99t put together this sort of package until it amasses more of it=
s teams=E2=80=99 local rights, which expire along various timelines. The Do=
dgers, for example, are contentedly locked into
their lucrative, $334 million deal=E2=80=94almost the <i>precise </i>value =
of their payroll=E2=80=94until 2038. And the Yankees, with their own R.S.N.=
 and O.T.T. option, may have other theories of the case.  <br/><br/>So far,=
 the teams that have turned over their rights are cognizant that they will =
bring in less local revenue, at least initially. But Manfred predicts teams=
 will wind up making more in the long run with a hybrid local media strateg=
y, one that combines cable carriage with local broadcast deals and pooled d=
irect-to-consumer offerings that might entice the trillion-dollar market ca=
p streaming players, like Amazon, Apple, and Google. =E2=80=9CThe inherent =
value of our content is going to bring us back to and beyond where we were,=
=E2=80=9D Manfred said. =E2=80=9CI would predict today that that trough wil=
l be shorter. I certainly am sensing in my private conversations=E2=80=94an=
d we=E2=80=99ve seen it publicly=E2=80=94that new media companies are becom=
ing aggressive sooner than some people expect.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>You
can listen to the <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI=
6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dTc2FGX1RRak44bm9lajlYM2Y5dz0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cH=
M6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvcG9kY2FzdF9lcGlzb2RlL21hbmZyZWRzLW1sYi1tYWdpYy8_dXRtX2Nhb=
XBhaWduPVRoZStWYXJzaXR5Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MTAlMkYyMSUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2=
dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9VGhlK1ZhcnNpdHkrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgxMCUyRjMlMkYyNCUyOVx=
1MDAyNnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWxfYWN0aW9uXHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b21lci5pb1=
x1MDAyNnV0bV90ZXJtPWY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNjA2MTdkY=
TQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua19pZCI6MTE0MjY3NH0/648c0444d25a103ca92044a0721d97df0b57=
3aaf9fd0cd452802e5dabdb88b9f" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;f=
ont-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">entirety</a></u> of our chat on the<i> Varsi=
ty </i>podcast. Meanwhile, enjoy excerpts from the best parts of our chat, =
below. As always, this conversation has been lightly edited and condensed f=
or clarity.<br/></td>
