          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><b><i>John Ourand</=
i>:</b> <b>MLB made headlines this month when it took back the rights to th=
e Guardians, Twins, and Brewers=E2=80=94in addition to the Padres, Diamondb=
acks, and Rockies=E2=80=94whose rights were held by Diamond Sports. From a =
50,000-foot view, what is your plan with these local rights?</b><br/><br/><=
i>Rob Manfred</i>: I think it=E2=80=99s important to remember that we didn=
=E2=80=99t begin with a grand plan about local rights or being in the busin=
ess of doing games locally. In a lot of ways, we stepped into a situation w=
here we didn=E2=80=99t have a great alternative. The R.S.N. was going bankr=
upt, and we needed to make sure that we got our games out locally. As we st=
arted to think about the landscape more generally, we came to realize that =
our broadcast product needed to be more national. The difficulties with the=
 R.S.N.s presented an opportunity for us to get
into a more centralized media strategy and get closer to the model that Com=
missioner<b> Adam Silver</b> used in his recent round of NBA negotiations. =
The R.S.N.s were really good for us from a financial perspective, but they =
did not give us a full opportunity [to optimize our] reach.<br/><br/>What I=
=E2=80=99d like to see happen over time is, we redo our national deals and =
convert some of that local inventory into national inventory, which in turn=
 increases our reach. We own the outer market rights already; if we control=
 local rights as well, we can sell anything, anywhere, and you don=E2=80=99=
t just have to sell in your market. I=E2=80=99d like to get into a mode whe=
re if it=E2=80=99s not in a national package, the consumer has the ability =
to go in and buy whatever he wants to watch, no matter where it is. And we =
get rid of that questionable business concept of the blackout.<br/><br/><b>=
Are you confident that you=E2=80=99re going to be able to bring big-market =
teams=E2=80=94the Dodgers, the Yankees, the Cubs,
for example=E2=80=94into that sort of system, which is going to ask them to=
 share more than they=E2=80=99re used to?</b><br/><br/>=E2=80=9CConfident=
=E2=80=9D is a funny word. I think there is a path forward that involves me=
dia and other really significant industry issues that could put all the clu=
bs in a position to come together. And the point I=E2=80=99d make about tha=
t is, the trends that are affecting the R.S.N.s right now, we=E2=80=99re se=
eing them first in our smaller markets. And that=E2=80=99s not surprising, =
right? But those trends are so fundamental, sooner or later, they=E2=80=99r=
e gonna affect everyone. And I do think there=E2=80=99s an opportunity in t=
hat problem.<br/><br/><b>I=E2=80=99ve always viewed the MLB=E2=80=99s untra=
ditional streaming deals with Roku and Apple as some sort of test. What hav=
e you learned from them?</b><br/><br/>I think Apple, in particular, has bee=
n really creative on the production end. And there are learnings there that=
 have been useful to us; some things worked, some things didn=E2=80=99t. Ou=
r traditional
broadcasts are kind of the same as they=E2=80=99ve been for a long time. Ev=
erything from graphics to announcers, Apple experimented with, and we=E2=80=
=99ve learned from that. <br/><br/>On the business side, I think maybe the =
biggest issue to talk about is the difference between having a paywall and =
not. We=E2=80=99ve had Apple in front of a paywall, we=E2=80=99ve had it be=
hind a paywall; we=E2=80=99ve had Roku in front of a paywall. I think the d=
iscussion and the differences between the distribution mechanisms that Appl=
e and Roku use, respectively, get to the underappreciated business issue in=
 broadcast for us, and that=E2=80=99s <i>reach</i>.<br/><br/>For years, we =
focused on dollars, understandably. But I think when you have a live busine=
ss that=E2=80=99s as robust as ours=E2=80=94where 72 million people a year =
go through the gates=E2=80=94reaching the fans with your broadcast is reall=
y important in terms of driving them to the ballpark, which is another real=
ly important part of our business. <br/><br/><b>The biggest
complaint about baseball for decades has been how old the fan base is. That=
=E2=80=99s starting to turn around. Why is that?</b><br/><br/>I think there=
 are several reasons. I do think the changes we=E2=80=99ve made to the way =
the game is played on the field are a big part of it. We did really fundame=
ntal research about what fans wanted to see. And I think we=E2=80=99re putt=
ing out there a more action-packed, tighter, quicker game that=E2=80=99s ap=
pealing to young people. Secondly, I think that we have been blessed with a=
n infusion of young and extraordinary talent, combined with a different att=
itude about interacting with fans, being accessible to fans, particularly b=
eing accessible on social media platforms where young people live. Then the=
 third thing=E2=80=94and this one gets overlooked=E2=80=94I think the clubs=
 have done a phenomenal job with what I refer to as <i>the program in the s=
tadium</i>. Now we see so many alternatives=E2=80=94more flexible seating a=
nd ticketing arrangements that are designed to meet the
desires of younger fans.<br/></td>
         </tr>
